04622nam a22007455i 9780801459924DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014599247 a10.7591/97808014599242doi  a(DE-B1597)480104  a(OCoLC)979627757  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJC571b.W146 2008eb 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a3232221 aWalldorf, C. William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJust Politics :bHuman Rights and the Foreign Policy of Great Powers /cC. William Walldorf. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b9 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Security Affairs00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Human Rights and Foreign Policy -- t1. Humanitarianism and Commitment Termination -- t2. Suffering Christians in British-Ottoman Relations -- t3. Torture and Summary Execution in U.S.–Latin American Relations -- t4. Apartheid in U.S.–South African Relations -- t5. Human Rights and Vital Security -- t6. The Implications of Enforced Humanitarian Norms -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMany foreign policy analysts assume that elite policymakers in liberal democracies consistently ignore humanitarian norms when these norms interfere with commercial and strategic interests. Today's endorsement by Western governments of repressive regimes in countries from Kazakhstan to Pakistan and Saudi Arabia in the name of fighting terror only reinforces this opinion. In Just Politics, C. William Walldorf Jr. challenges this conventional wisdom, arguing that human rights concerns have often led democratic great powers to sever vital strategic partnerships even when it has not been in their interest to do so.Walldorf sets out his case in detailed studies of British alliance relationships with the Ottoman Empire and Portugal in the nineteenth century and of U.S. partnerships with numerous countries—ranging from South Africa, Turkey, Greece and El Salvador to Nicaragua, Chile, and Argentina—during the Cold War. He finds that illiberal behavior by partner states, varying degrees of pressure by nonstate actors, and legislative activism account for the decisions by democracies to terminate strategic partnerships for human rights reasons.To demonstrate the central influence of humanitarian considerations and domestic politics in the most vital of strategic moments of great-power foreign policy, Walldorf argues that Western governments can and must integrate human rights into their foreign policies. Failure to take humanitarian concerns into account, he contends, will only damage their long-term strategic objectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAlliances. 0aHuman rights. 0aInternational relations. 4aHumanities & Human Rights. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSecurity Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145992440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801459924423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801459924/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK